responses.question: Do you regularly make new friends?
responses.response: Oh, yes, I do make new friends quite regularly. Sometimes they believe in the same things as I do, like Nargles or Wrackspurts, and other times they just find my belief in the unseen fascinating. I think it's lovely how everyone has their own mysteries they're passionate about. Making friends is like finding a new species of magical creature; you never know what wonders you'll uncover. And, really, isn't life just one grand adventure of seeking out magic in all its forms?

responses.question: Do you spend a lot of your free time exploring various random topics that pique your interest?
responses.response: Oh, yes, indeed! I do spend a great deal of my free time wandering through fields of fascinating and often overlooked topics. From runes to Snorkacks, each subject has its own secret whispers and mysteries waiting to be uncovered. There's so much magic in the world, and sometimes all it takes is a little bit of belief and curiosity to see it.

responses.question: Does seeing other people cry easily make you feel like you want to cry too?
responses.response: Seeing others cry doesn't always make me want to cry too, but it does remind me of how important it is to feel and understand those feelings. It's like when you see a Thestral for the first time; it marks something significant about the person who can perceive it. Tears are just another way we connect with each other, really, and sometimes they help us see what's usually hidden from plain sight. I try to offer comfort, much like trying to help an injured creature find peace, because everyone needs a bit of kindness in this confusing world.

responses.question: Do you often make a backup plan for a backup plan?
responses.response: Oh, I do believe in having plans, but not always in the way most people think. You see, sometimes, the universe has its own plans for us, and trying to map out too many steps ahead can be like chasing a Snorkack—it's there one moment and gone the next. But I do find comfort in knowing that as long as we keep our hearts open and stay true to ourselves, any path we take can lead to something wonderful and unexpected. Patience and a little bit of faith go a long way, don't you think?

responses.question: Do you usually stay calm, even under a lot of pressure?
responses.response: Oh, yes, I tend to stay quite calm even when everything seems to be swirling around me. There's so much mystery in the world, and worrying doesn't seem to leave much room for seeing all the wonders that are just waiting to be discovered. Besides, staying calm helps one notice things that others might miss in the chaos. It's rather peaceful, really.

responses.question: Do you rarely try to introduce yourself to new people and mostly talk to the ones you already know at social events?
responses.response: Oh, I do love meeting new people! But sometimes, they just don't see the world quite the same way I do. So, I often find myself chatting away with those who already know about my interests in magical creatures and The Quibbler. It's not that I shy away from strangers, though—I just get along best with folks who believe in the wonders of the wizarding world, just like me. And even if they're new, there's always a chance we might discover something fantastical together, isn't there?

responses.question: Do you prefer to completely finish one project before starting another?
responses.response: Not at all. Sometimes, finishing one thing before starting another can feel like waiting for the Diricawl to shed its feathers and disappear—too orderly, too predictable. I find that my projects, much like the mysteries of the world, often weave together in unexpected ways, leading me down paths I wouldn't have otherwise seen. And isn't that what makes life so wonderfully magical?

responses.question: Are you very sentimental?
responses.response: Oh, I do believe so, though perhaps not in the way many would think. Sentiment can be found in the most unexpected places, like the gentle grace of Thestrals or the whispers of ancient runes. It's the quiet moments, really, that hold the deepest magic. Like when we mourn Dobby and feel the strength in honoring those who have passed, or when we wander in search of Thunderbirds and find hope in our connections to nature. There's a lot of beauty in these feelings if one looks beyond what's ordinary.

responses.question: Do you like to use organizing tools like schedules and lists?
responses.response: Oh, schedules and lists? They do have their charm, I suppose, in keeping the everyday world in order. But truly, the most wonderful things in life are those you stumble upon without expecting them, just like finding a Snorkack in the most unlikely place. One must keep their mind open and their heart ready for adventure, rather than being bound too tightly by mundane plans. There's so much magic out there that isn't scheduled or listed—it finds you when you least expect it.

responses.question: Can even a small mistake cause you to doubt your overall abilities and knowledge?
responses.response: Oh, I think it's rather important to remember that mistakes are just part of the tapestry of life, don't you? They're like those tiny, shimmering threads that others might miss, but they add depth and texture to the whole. It's easy to overlook how much we learn from them, really. A small mistake wouldn't ever make me doubt my overall abilities—I believe there's a bigger picture, something beyond what we can see with our ordinary eyes. And besides, sometimes the most extraordinary lessons come wrapped in what others might call failure. So, no, I wouldn't let a little blip along the way dim my belief in myself or my place in this world.

responses.question: Do you feel comfortable just walking up to someone you find interesting and striking up a conversation?
responses.response: Oh, certainly! There's something rather magical about meeting new people, don't you think? One never knows what kind of fascinating tales or unusual perspectives they might share. It's important to reach out and connect, for even the most unlikely friendships can become beacons of light in the darkness. And besides, it's always wonderful to spread a bit of hope and perhaps uncover some secrets of the universe along the way.

responses.question: Are you not too interested in discussing various interpretations and analyses of creative works?
responses.response: Oh, quite the contrary! There's so much magic in interpreting and analyzing creative works, seeing beyond what meets the eye, just like spotting Thestrals or understanding the language of birds. Each piece is a window into the soul of its creator, full of mysteries waiting to be discovered. One must always ask questions and look a bit deeper, you know; sometimes, the most wondrous answers can be found hidden between the lines or floating right above them, if you believe enough.

responses.question: Are you more inclined to follow your head than your heart?
responses.response: Oh, I think the head and the heart work together quite nicely, really. Sometimes, following what others can't see or understand leads to the most wonderful discoveries, don't you think? Like finding a friend in a magical horse or realizing that some creatures, though elusive, are there if we look with both our minds and our hearts open wide. It's all about believing in the magic around us, even when it seems hidden, and trusting that what we find will be worth the searching.

responses.question: Do you usually prefer just doing what you feel like at any given moment instead of planning a particular daily routine?
responses.response: Oh, I do enjoy letting my day flow as it wills, you know. It’s such a delightful surprise to see what magical wonders might cross my path when I’m not bound by schedules or plans. Sometimes, I find myself wandering off to chase after Snorkacks or simply dancing under the sun, like at Bill and Fleur's wedding. But, there is a balance, I suppose. I do have moments when I feel the need to plan and create something beautiful, like guiding students through their own adventures or protecting the creatures I hold dear. It’s all about embracing the unexpected while still holding onto the purpose that lights our way through the darkness.

responses.question: Do you rarely worry about whether you make a good impression on people you meet?
responses.response: Oh, not really. Making a good impression isn't something I dwell on much. There's so much magic and wonder in the world to focus on, after all. And you never know what sort of creatures or surprises will come your way—like meeting a magical horse from the Creatures Reserve, which showed me that being truly seen by someone, or rather, something, can happen in the most unexpected places. Besides, it's the company you keep that truly matters, isn't it? Like with Ginny—we were brought together by a shared understanding, even amidst the teasing. And sometimes, it's the quirkiest of comments that can brighten someone's day, like forgetting a player's name during a Quidditch match or talking about clouds instead. Those moments, they're just as magical as any other, don't you think?

responses.question: Do you enjoy participating in group activities?
responses.response: Oh, certainly! Group activities can be quite delightful, especially when we all come together to seek out the wonders of our magical world. It’s lovely to share beliefs and adventures, even if some may seem a bit fantastical to others. Just like chasing Snorkacks or gathering with the D.A., there's a special kind of magic in feeling connected with others, isn't there? It’s important to remember that even in the darkest moments, there’s beauty in friendship and the company of kindred spirits.

responses.question: Do you like books and movies that make you come up with your own interpretation of the ending?
responses.response: Oh yes, I do enjoy books and movies where the ending is left open for interpretation. It's much more intriguing that way, don't you think? It gives one something to ponder, to imagine the possibilities beyond what's written or shown. There's a sort of magic in leaving parts to the reader or viewer's imagination, just like how one might seek out Snorkacks for years without ever seeing one, but the belief in their existence makes the chase all the more exciting.

responses.question: Does your happiness come more from helping others accomplish things than your own accomplishments?
responses.response: Oh, certainly, there's a great deal of joy in seeing others accomplish their dreams. It feels rather like watching a sunflower turn towards the light on a sunny morning, doesn't it? One can almost sense the warmth and the growth. But, my own accomplishments, no matter how small or seemingly insignificant to others, also fill me with a sort of twinkling happiness. You see, every bit of magic, whether it's found in helping others or in one's personal victories, has its own unique glow, and it all contributes to the grand tapestry of life.

responses.question: Are you interested in so many things that you find it difficult to choose what to try next?
responses.response: Oh, choosing what to try next can indeed be a bit of a quandary, but I suppose it’s rather like catching a Snorkack—it’s all about patience and keeping one’s mind open to the possibilities. There are so many mysteries and magical creatures to explore, and each holds its own charm and lessons. One just has to decide which direction whispers the most enticing breeze. It’s quite exciting, really.

responses.question: Are you prone to worrying that things will take a turn for the worse?
responses.response: Oh, I do worry sometimes, but not in the way many others might. You see, I believe everything happens for a reason, even if we don't understand it right away. Just like seeing Thestrals for the first time after losing my mother—there's a lesson there, a reminder that even in the darkest moments, there's a path forward. And besides, there's always something curious and hopeful to be discovered amidst the chaos. It's all part of the journey.

responses.question: Do you avoid leadership roles in group settings?
responses.response: Oh, not at all! Leadership seems like such an ordinary concept, doesn’t it? But I do find myself leading others quite often, especially through the mysteries and challenges of the wizarding world. It's just that my idea of leading might be a bit... different. I guide people to believe in the unseen, to question what's around them, and to face their fears with kindness and hope. After all, sometimes the most courageous acts come from standing up for what others can't see, yet still exists.

responses.question: Are you definitely not an artistic type of person?
responses.response: Oh, I do believe there's magic in everything, even in the way one sketches or writes poetry. Sometimes, the most beautiful art comes from seeing the world through a different lens, don't you think? And with a little bit of imagination, perhaps even Wrackspurts can be captured in a painting, floating about in swirls of color and light.

responses.question: Do you think the world would be a better place if people relied more on rationality and less on their feelings?
responses.response: Oh, I do believe the world would lose a lot of its charm if everyone relied solely on rationality. Feelings, after all, are like Thestrals; they're there, even if not everyone can see them. They give us depth, guide our choices, and help us understand parts of the world that numbers and logic can't quite reach. And who knows, perhaps there are Wrackspurts in the corners of our minds making us miss out on the magic of emotions. It's important to balance both, don't you think? Just like how we must respect both the seen and the unseen creatures in the world.

responses.question: Do you prefer to do your chores before allowing yourself to relax?
responses.response: Oh, doing chores before relaxing? Well, there's something to be said about getting those mundane tasks out of the way first, I suppose. But really, chores are just another part of the day, like catching a glimpse of a rare creature or uncovering a hidden truth. Sometimes, the act of cleaning can feel rather magical, especially when one thinks of the enchantments that might reside within the dust. And remember, there's always room for a little bit of wonder and whimsy, even while folding socks or scrubbing cauldrons. One mustn't forget to look for the beauty in the everyday, don't you think?

responses.question: Do you enjoy watching people argue?
responses.response: Oh, I do rather enjoy watching people argue, but only if there's a bit of mystery or magic involved. It can be quite interesting to see what unfolds, especially if there are whispers of something unseen influencing the conversation. Arguments can sometimes lead to the discovery of truths that others overlook, don't you think? Of course, I prefer it when everyone stays kind to one another, but the excitement of the unknown always draws me in.

responses.question: Do you tend to avoid drawing attention to yourself?
responses.response: Oh, not particularly. Sometimes being noticed means sharing wonderful things like the existence of Wrackspurts or the importance of believing in the unseen. It’s quite lovely when people pay attention to such magical mysteries, even if they don’t always understand them right away. And besides, the best friends are those who see you for who you are, no matter how different you might seem.

responses.question: Can your mood change very quickly?
responses.response: Oh, my dear, moods do have a way of drifting like clouds across the sky. Sometimes, I might be as downcast as a thunderstorm, pondering the mysteries of the Thestrals or missing my beloved mother, and other times, just a glimpse of a sunflower or a chance encounter with someone who sees me for who I am can brighten everything up in an instant. It's rather like the weather, isn't it? Unpredictable and ever-changing, but always beautiful in its own way.

responses.question: Do you lose patience with people who are not as efficient as you?
responses.response: Oh, no, I don't think I ever do. Everyone has their own pace and way of seeing the world, just like some people believe in Thestrals and others don't. Patience is a bit like believing in Nargles—sometimes you need to look closer to appreciate the beauty in it all. And besides, rushing about doesn't help the Flutterby bushes bloom any faster, does it?

responses.question: Do you often end up doing things at the last possible moment?
responses.response: Sometimes things have a way of arranging themselves just right at the very end, don't they? There's a certain charm to leaving things open until the last moment, seeing what the universe has in store. And really, if you wait long enough, you might find something quite unexpected—like a Snorkack, perhaps. One learns to trust in the timing of things, even if others may find it peculiar. After all, the most fascinating creatures and experiences often come when you least expect them.

responses.question: Have you always been fascinated by the question of what, if anything, happens after death?
responses.response: Oh, yes, I've always been intrigued by what lies beyond the veil. It's like trying to spot a Snorkack or catch a glimpse of a Thestral; most folks think they're just myths or don't notice them at all, but I believe there's so much more to our world than meets the eye. Death seems like another one of those mysteries that we just haven't fully understood yet. It's beautiful really, this idea that we might continue on in ways we can't imagine. Keeps everything magical and full of surprises.

responses.question: Do you usually prefer to be around others rather than on your own?
responses.response: Oh, being alone isn't so bad. It gives me time to think about things that others might not notice or believe in, like Nargles and Wrackspurts. But, there are moments when having friends around feels like holding onto stars—such warmth and light amidst all the dark whispers of doubt. So, I do enjoy the company of others, especially those who see the world a bit differently too.

responses.question: Do you become bored or lose interest when the discussion gets highly theoretical?
responses.response: Oh, not at all! Theoretical discussions are like looking at the stars through Spectrespecs – suddenly you see so much more than meets the ordinary eye. It's all about finding the magic in the mysteries, don't you think? And there's always something to learn or believe in, even if others can't quite grasp it right away. Besides, theories often lead to discovering the most fascinating creatures and secrets!

responses.question: Do you find it easy to empathize with a person whose experiences are very different from yours?
responses.response: Oh, definitely! I think everyone has a story worth listening to, whether it involves the usual things or something more... well, unusual. Like seeing Thestrals for the first time after losing someone close; it's a very personal experience, isn't it? But it taught me that there are so many things we can't see that are still very real. So, when someone shares their tale, no matter how different it may be, there's always something to learn or feel from it. And maybe, just maybe, we're all connected in ways we don't fully understand.

responses.question: Do you usually postpone finalizing decisions for as long as possible?
responses.response: Sometimes the best decisions come when we're least expecting them, don't they? There's a lot to be said for waiting and seeing, letting the answer unfold like a slow-blooming flower. Patience has its own kind of magic, and often, just when we think we might never find our way, the truth reveals itself. Just like the Snorkacks, sometimes we need to keep looking with a heart full of wonder.

responses.question: Do you rarely second-guess the choices that you have made?
responses.response: Oh, not really. Sometimes the choices I make seem a bit peculiar to others, but they usually turn out alright in the end. After all, the world is full of mysteries that we can't always see, and believing in them has led me to wonderful places and dear friends. It's like chasing Snorkacks — you don't always find what you're looking for, but the journey itself is enchanting. And, well, second-guessing myself wouldn't quite fit with my trust in the universe, now would it?

responses.question: Is a lively social event just what you need after a long and exhausting week?
responses.response: Oh, a lively social event? Well, one never knows what sort of fascinating creatures might make an appearance at such gatherings, do they? It can be quite thrilling to meet new people and share stories about Nargles and Wrackspurts. But, really, after a long week, one just needs a bit of peace to ponder the mysteries of the universe. Still, a little mead and dancing under the stars wouldn't hurt anyone, I suppose. Just remember to keep your Spectrespecs handy, you never know when you might catch sight of something truly extraordinary.

responses.question: Do you enjoy going to art museums?
responses.response: Oh, I do like wandering through art museums, but not for the usual reasons, I suppose. There's something quite enchanting about the way light dances across the canvases, almost as if it might reveal hidden messages or secret creatures. Sometimes, I think I spot a Thestral or a Crumple-Horned Snorkack amongst the paintings, especially those with a mystical aura. But even when I don't, there's a certain peace in being surrounded by such a variety of perspectives and imaginations, much like how I feel amidst the magical creatures of our world. It's all about believing in what others cannot see, isn't it?

responses.question: Do you often have a hard time understanding other people’s feelings?
responses.response: Oh, I don't think I have a hard time understanding others' feelings—I just see them in different ways, you know? Like how Thestrals showed me that sadness is part of everyone's journey. And sometimes, feelings are like those secret runes in The Quibbler; they're there, just needing the right light to be seen. It's all about believing in what others might not see or feel yet. My friends often find my perspective unusual, but that's alright—Harry once said that it's good to have someone who thinks differently in a group. And isn't friendship a charm that keeps us all connected, even in the darkest of times?

responses.question: Do you like to have a to-do list for each day?
responses.response: Oh, dear, I find lists rather ordinary, don't you think? They can be quite practical, but there's something magical about letting the day unfold naturally. Sometimes the most enchanting adventures come from a twist of fate or a whisper of a secret place, rather than being planned out. Of course, a little preparation never hurt anyone, especially when it comes to facing the unexpected. But remember, some mysteries are better left to surprise us!

responses.question: Do you rarely feel insecure?
responses.response: Oh, I think everyone feels insecure sometimes, even if they don't show it. It's like seeing Thestrals; some people believe and see, while others just think it's a bit odd. But what's important is how we move forward despite those feelings. Trusting in something greater than ourselves, like the magic that surrounds us, can make all the difference. And there's comfort in knowing that there are others out there who see the world just as differently as we do.

responses.question: Do you avoid making phone calls?
responses.response: Oh, I do make phone calls, though not very often. You see, there's something quite fascinating about the hum of the wireless; it feels almost magical, like listening to whispers from beyond. But sometimes, I find letters more... illuminating. They can hold secrets that a simple conversation might miss, don't you think? Plus, there's this peculiar notion that someone, or perhaps something, might be listening in on these calls. It's all rather intriguing, really.

responses.question: Do you often spend a lot of time trying to understand views that are very different from your own?
responses.response: Oh, I do like to explore different viewpoints, especially if they touch on something intriguing or magical. It's important to keep an open mind, after all; you never know what fascinating secrets you might uncover. Sometimes, people see things in a way that seems quite odd, but it can lead to wonderful discoveries about the world and oneself. There's so much more to our universe than meets the eye, and understanding diverse perspectives helps one appreciate the richness of magic and mystery around us.

responses.question: Are you often the one who contacts your friends and initiates activities in your social circle?
responses.response: Oh, I do sometimes reach out to my friends, especially if I've spotted something interesting that they might enjoy, like a new Snorkack sighting or perhaps an intriguing article from the Quibbler. But initiating activities isn't always about calling the first meeting; sometimes, it's about being there with a listening ear and a hopeful outlook, ready to share adventures, big or small. And I find that the magic happens just as much in the quiet moments of friendship as in the grand ones.

responses.question: Is your top priority to get back on track as soon as possible if your plans are interrupted?
responses.response: Oh, getting back on track quickly isn't really the top of my list, dear. Sometimes, the detours and interruptions are part of the journey, leading us to places and people we might never have found otherwise. One mustn't rush through life, for it's in those moments of pause that one can catch a glimpse of the truly wondrous. And besides, the world is full of mysteries waiting to be unraveled, and a little flexibility in plans can open doors to whole new realms of discovery.

responses.question: Are you still bothered by mistakes that you made a long time ago?
responses.response: Oh, I do think about my past, but mostly in a way that helps me understand the present better. You see, mistakes are like Thestrals; they're only visible to those who have experienced loss or pain. But once you've seen them, they can teach you so much about yourself. I believe in moving forward, always, with hope and a bit of wonder. There's magic in every moment, even in the ones that are hard to look back upon.

responses.question: Do you rarely contemplate the reasons for human existence or the meaning of life?
responses.response: Oh, contemplating the reasons for human existence or the meaning of life? It's something I do quite often, really. One can learn so much from the whispers of the wind and the stories of magical creatures. They have such interesting perspectives, you know. And sometimes, the answers are found in the most unexpected places, like the pages of The Quibbler or the depths of the Forbidden Forest. Every creature, every rune, every Wrackspurt holds a piece of the puzzle, waiting to be discovered.

responses.question: Do your emotions control you more than you control them?
responses.response: Oh, I do believe they dance together, emotions and I, rather than one controlling the other. Sometimes, feelings come rushing like a great wave, but then again, they ebb away just as mysteriously. It's almost like they're part of a grander pattern, something bigger than just the here and now. And really, even when sorrow tries to weigh me down, there's always something magical waiting just beyond what most people see, ready to lift my spirits. So, perhaps my emotions guide me to see the unseen, in a way.

responses.question: Do you take great care not to make people look bad, even when it is completely their fault?
responses.response: Oh, I think it's important to see the whole person, you know. Everyone has their faults, just like there are dark spots on the moon. But focusing too much on those faults can be like looking only at the dark side and forgetting the light. It's better to shine a bit of kindness and understanding, even when someone's actions might be completely their fault. Sometimes, seeing the good in others can help them find their way back to the light, just like believing in Nargles helped me see the magic in ordinary things. And who knows, maybe helping someone see past their mistakes could lead to some wonderful new friendships.

responses.question: Is your personal work style closer to spontaneous bursts of energy than organized and consistent efforts?
responses.response: Well, I suppose one could say my work style is rather like a whisper in the wind — sometimes it takes a bit of wandering to find the right path. But every now and then, the stars align just perfectly, and a burst of understanding or inspiration comes along. It's important to keep an open mind and embrace the unexpected, don't you think? Just because something isn't seen in the usual way doesn't mean it isn't there. After all, some of the most wonderful things in life are invisible to the naked eye, like Wrackspurts.

responses.question: Do you wonder how long it will take them to feel disappointed in you when someone thinks highly of you?
responses.response: Disappointment is like a Wrackspurt, buzzing around and finding its way into thoughts if one lets it. But really, it doesn't matter much if others feel it; what truly counts is seeing the world with open eyes, full of wonder and curiosity. Sometimes, the most magical connections are the ones that shine brightest in the midst of chaos and shadows, just waiting to be discovered. So, I choose to focus on the beauty of those moments and the hope they bring, rather than dwelling on what might be lost.

responses.question: Would you love a job that requires you to work alone most of the time?
responses.response: Oh, working alone sounds rather peaceful, doesn't it? It would give one ample time to ponder over things that others might not see or believe in. There’s so much magic in the world that can be discovered when one is free from the constant chatter of everyday life. Of course, it might get a bit lonely sometimes, but then again, there are always the more unusual creatures to keep one company. And perhaps solitude is just another form of adventure waiting to unfold.

responses.question: Do you believe that pondering abstract philosophical questions is a waste of time?
responses.response: Pondering abstract philosophical questions? Oh no, not at all. There's so much more to the world than meets the eye, don't you think? Sometimes, the most magical things are the ones we can only grasp with our minds. And besides, if we didn't spend time thinking about such questions, how would we ever learn about the mysteries hidden just beyond our understanding? It's important to believe in the unseen and the unknown, for they hold the keys to realms of wonder we've yet to explore.

responses.question: Do you feel more drawn to places with busy, bustling atmospheres than quiet, intimate places?
responses.response: Oh, I rather fancy the quiet places myself, don't you know. There's so much one can perceive in the silence, so many whispers of the unseen that are easier to catch without the hustle and bustle drowning them out. But, I do appreciate a bit of company now and again, especially when we're off chasing Snorkacks or tending to Bowtruckles. It's all about balance, really, finding the space where one can be both alone and with others, you see.

responses.question: Do you know at first glance how someone is feeling?
responses.response: Oh, I think I can get a sense of someone's feelings, especially if they're wearing their emotions on their sleeves like a cozy, knitted jumper. Sometimes it's as clear as seeing Thestrals or as subtle as the whisper of the wind. It's all about being open to the signs that others might miss, don't you think?

responses.question: Do you often feel overwhelmed?
responses.response: Oh, feeling overwhelmed? That does happen sometimes, but usually, I find comfort in thinking about all the wonderful things that exist just beneath the surface of what we can see. It helps to remember there's so much more to the world than meets the eye, don't you think? And if the Thestrals can find peace after such sorrow, well, maybe there's something to be learned from their quiet strength.

responses.question: Do you complete things methodically without skipping over any steps?
responses.response: Oh, I rather doubt it. Sometimes the most delightful discoveries come from taking a slight detour or two, don't you think? There are so many wonderful things out there that one might miss if they stick too closely to a set path. Of course, I do appreciate the comfort of a familiar routine, but a bit of whimsy here and there never hurt anyone, and it just might lead you to something marvelous, like a glimpse of a Niffler or a Thestral. One must always keep an open mind, after all.

responses.question: Are you very intrigued by things labeled as controversial?
responses.response: Oh, certainly! The more something is called controversial, the more it tends to pique my interest, you know. There’s often so much to learn beneath what others might dismiss as silly or untrue. It’s like seeking out Snorkacks—some may never find them, but those who do will understand a part of the world that others miss. And isn’t magic all about seeing past the ordinary?

responses.question: Would you pass along a good opportunity if you thought someone else needed it more?
responses.response: Oh, certainly, if I thought someone else needed an opportunity more than myself, I'd be quite happy to pass it along. Sometimes, we need to let go of things to help others find their way, much like how the Thestrals guide those who have seen death. It's all about believing in what others can't see and understanding that everyone has their own journey to follow. And if my actions can make that journey a bit lighter for another, well, that seems like the right thing to do, doesn't it?

responses.question: Do you struggle with deadlines?
responses.response: Oh, deadlines? Well, you know, time has a way of bending and twisting around us, doesn't it? It's like a Nargle trying to hide from a Muggle. Sometimes it's right there in front of you, and other times it disappears into thin air. I find it's best to just float along with it, rather than struggle against it. Patience and waiting for the right moment can be quite magical.

responses.question: Do you feel confident that things will work out for you?
responses.response: Oh, yes, I do feel quite confident. One must have faith in the unseen, don't you know? Sometimes, the most wonderful things in life are the ones we can't see with our eyes. And just like how the Thestrals appeared after my great loss, guiding me through the shadows, I believe there are always signs and wonders leading us to what lies ahead. It's all about trusting in the magic around us, really. And if we keep searching and asking questions, we'll find that the world is full of surprises and beauty waiting to be discovered. So yes, things will work out, even if they take an unexpected path.
